Event Forwarding Requirements in Windows define the necessary configurations and conditions that must be met for successful collection of event logs between source computers and a central collector system. This feature is part of the Windows event management framework developed by Microsoft and relies on technologies such as WinRM and the WS-Management protocol for communication.
Event forwarding operates in two modes—collector-initiated and source-initiated—and each has specific requirements for proper functioning.
1. Requirements for Collector-Initiated Subscription
In a collector-initiated subscription, the collector computer initiates the connection and retrieves event logs from source systems.
Key Requirements:
1. Administrative Permissions
The collector system must have administrator access on all source computers to retrieve event logs.
2. WinRM Configuration
WinRM must be enabled and configured on both collector and source systems
Proper listeners (HTTP/HTTPS) must be set up
3. Network Connectivity
Reliable network communication between collector and source computers
Required ports (5985 for HTTP, 5986 for HTTPS) must be open
4. Firewall Configuration
Windows Firewall must allow WinRM traffic
Exceptions should be configured for remote management
5. Event Log Access
Source systems must allow remote access to event logs
Necessary permissions should be granted
6. Subscription Configuration
The collector must define:
Source computer names
Event types to collect
Log filters
7. Time Synchronization
Systems should have synchronized time to ensure accurate event logging
2. Requirements for Source-Initiated Subscription
In a source-initiated subscription, the source computers initiate the connection and send events to the collector.
Key Requirements:
1. Group Policy Configuration
Source computers are configured using Group Policy
Policy specifies the collector server address
2. WinRM Configuration
WinRM must be enabled on both source and collector systems
Proper listeners must be configured
3. Event Forwarding Configuration
Source systems must be configured to forward specific events
Collector must define subscription settings
4. Network and Firewall Settings
Network connectivity must be established
Required ports (5985/5986) must be open
Firewall rules must allow communication
5. Permissions and Authentication
Proper authentication (Kerberos, NTLM, etc.) must be configured
Source systems must trust the collector
6. Subscription Manager Configuration
The collector must be defined as a subscription manager
Source systems use this configuration to send events
7. Scalability Considerations
Suitable for large environments with many source systems
Group Policy simplifies configuration across multiple machines
Common Requirements for Both Types
WinRM Service must be running on all systems
WS-Management protocol must be supported
Proper authentication and security settings must be configured
Systems must be part of the same domain or have trust relationships (for Kerberos)
Event Viewer must be available for viewing collected logs
